post_text:
Fan Protocols for game at MILFORD on 9/4/2020:
-The crowd will not be limited but seating is limited. Bleacher seating will be limited to about 250 spots for Bluejay fans. It is not a large grandstand and they are allowed 75% capacity.
-Students in MSHS will sit on the hill south of the grandstand. It is recommended to bring blankest. Students in student section WILL be REQUIRED to wear masks the entire time.
-Cheerleaders can lead cheers. Cheerleaders will be required to mask up. Space may require cheer squad to split (as at home).
-Overflow fans may sit on hill (likely too steep for chairs) or may stand on track (where marked) or may bring chair for grass area in the SOUTH endzone. Please keep chairs off of track surface.
-Milford will broadcast the game on https://trst.in/sq5Nk9

post_text:
The Ashland-Greenwood Public Schools is taking a census of children living in the school district from birth through age 18. Any baby born through June 30th of the current year will be included for the current year’s census. Bev Hohensee will be conducting the count for the school district. The census is used for reporting a count of all children to the State of Nebraska by ages and is also used by the district for program planning.

If your children are already attending school here, we have that information, but if you have younger children, and haven’t already given us that information, we need their information by June 30. We collect parents' names, address, phone number, email, children's names, DOB, & gender.

Please email the information to me at bev.hohensee@agps.org or send to Ashland-Greenwood Public Schools District Office, Attn. Bev Hohensee, 1842 Furnas Street, Ashland, NE 68003.

Please, every Nebraskan and everyone in your family to go to https://www.testnebraska.com.

We encourage you to share this message with your employees, friends, family, neighbors and communities.
As always, we appreciate all of you and the role you play in communicating these important messages with the residents of Saunders County. Be Well!

post_text:
GRADUATION:
We would host an event if crowd ‘limits’ were raised to at least 250. This would allow for graduates and 2 people per graduate to be in our facility plus the essential personnel to run the event (and if limit was larger, then more family would be allowed). Here is our current alternate plan for holding a ceremony that will always be based on health department guidance and approval:

Sunday, July 26, 2:30 pm. With a two-week lead time (July 12, 2020) If guidance were received by 7/12/20 that we could have at least 250 people gather (or more) we would host the event on July 26. If NOT, we would move to our alternate date.

Alternate date: Saturday, August 8, 2:30 pm. Again, with a 2 week lead time (July 25, 2020). If guidance were received by 7/25/2020 that we could have at least 250 people gather (or more) we would host the event on Saturday, August 8.

Please, every Nebraskan and everyone in your family to go to https://www.testnebraska.com.
Then complete the questionnaire you find there. If we are going to kill the virus, crush the virus, slow the virus we must know more about where the virus is and who needs to be tested.

We encourage you to share this message with your employees, friends, family, neighbors and communities.
As always, we appreciate all of you and the role you play in communicating these important messages with the residents of Saunders County. Be Well!

Nebraska Department of Education - Request for Stakeholder Feedback (April 30, 2020)
The United States Congress passed the Coronavirus Aid, Relief, And Economic Security (CARES) Act, which includes one-time relief funding for local school districts, intended to address challenges of providing education during the COVID-19 pandemic.
The Nebraska Department of Education is seeking feedback from all stakeholders to understand local needs as well as potential investments and supports. Please take a moment to complete this short survey, also available in Spanish:
­­https://nde.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_efislqh4QDEA1KZ
Deadline to complete this survey is Monday, May 11, 2020.

post_text:
MESSAGE TO CURRENT 10th & 11th Graders:
We are excited to offer two new science courses for the 20-21 school year.
The course descriptions are below. Students need 30 credits (3 years) of science for graduation requirements. These courses CAN fulfill a science requirement.

Check your email for more information:
ANATOMY & PHYSIOLOGY
DESCRIPTION: Study of biology that relates to the structure and relationship between body parts and the relationship between the function of body parts and the body as a whole.

PRINCIPLES OF TECHNOLOGY & ROBOTICS
DESCRIPTION: This course applies physics content to prepare students for effectively for a technical career by exploring current and future use of automation technology. This course will apply principles of force, power, energy, resistance, and time among others. Application of these principals while engaging in a Robotics platform.

From NSAA: Boys Basketball Ticket Refund UPDATED Information
MARCH 17, 2020
If you purchased tickets online through GoFan, you will be refunded by them and will receive an email when you have been refunded. This process began Wednesday afternoon, March 11.
If you purchased tickets at the Pinnacle Bank Arena box office, you’ll need to return the tickets by mail to the NSAA. Please mail to: NSAA, Attn: Megan at 500 Charleston Street, Suite 1; Lincoln, NE 68508.
If you pre-purchased tickets through the NSAA, you should have received an email from Megan Huber, NSAA Business Manager. If you did not, please email Megan, mhuber@nsaahome.org.

post_text:
From the Nebraska School Activities Association (NSAA):
APRIL 2, 2020
All remaining NSAA activity practices and competitions, including district and state competitions, have been cancelled for this school year. These cancellations are part of a new Directed Health Measure issued by Governor Ricketts.
Bylaw 3.2.7 (Summer Activities) will go into effect on May 26th. In the interim, Bylaw 3.2.6.1 (School-Year, Out-of-Season) is expected to be followed by all member school athletic programs.
The NSAA continues to encourage all member schools to follow CDC, local, state and federal health department recommendations.
Any further official updates will be posted on the NSAA website and the NSAA social media platforms.

post_text:
As we work to provide learning opportunities for your students during this extended closure, we recognize this may pose a challenge to some. Your AGPS District Tech. Team is here to help!

Initially, our priority is to collect information from families who may not currently have internet access at home or whose children may not have access to a device at home that can be used for school work.

If your family/your child does not currently have access to the internet and/or access to a device that can be used for school work - please complete the following survey. Again, only those who are without technology resources at home at this time need to complete the survey.

Our first priority will be to work with families needing access at home. In the future, we will share information with all families about how to contact us if assistance or troubleshooting tech. issues at home is needed.

LINK TO SURVEY: https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/AGTech2020

Matt Flynn
Technology Integration Specialist
Ashland-Greenwood Public Schools
402-944-2114

Finally, there will be no school on Friday, March 13th due to a planned vacation day.

post_text:
It has been reported that Fremont Public Schools evacuated and canceled today's youth wrestling meet as a precautionary decision related to the Coronavirus. As a district, we felt it was important to provide notification regarding the fact that AGPS families and students were in attendance at this meet. We will continue to keep you informed regarding additional and relevant information.
Once again, we encourage you to remain informed about the spread of the coronavirus, and would recommend that you visit the website for the Department of Health and Human Services, found here, for further information as it develops. We would also encourage you to use this opportunity to remind your students of the importance of getting rest and washing hands, especially during cold and flu season.
Nebraska Department of Health and Human Services Website:
http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Coronavirus.aspx
Nebraska Coronavirus Hotline: (402) 444-3400, Monday-Friday 8:30 a.m. - 4:30 p.m
